  "answer": "**No work in the Falsafa corpus contains this exact quote or comparison.**\n\nI conducted multiple searches using distinctive phrases from the query (\"ten English workers\" \"fifty Russian slaves\", \"English lord\" \"Russian lord\", \"ten times richer\" \"single slave\", \"ten\" \"fifty\" slaves, \"english\" \"russian\" slaves, \"lord\" \"slaves\" \"richer\", and variations with \"serf\", \"workers\", \"labour\", \"emancipated\", \"free labour\"), prioritizing English translations. These yielded 0 direct hits or close matches.\n\nI also:\n- Read full chapters with potential relevance (Dunoyer *Nouveau traité d'économie* Vol I ch. 4, 11, 12; Comte *Traité de la propriété* Vol I ch. 1).\n- Checked snippets mentioning English/Russian contexts or slavery/serfdom (e.g., Dunoyer Vol I ch. 3, 7; Comte *Traité de législation* Vol II ch. 8, Vol III ch. 28).\n- Listed chapters in relevant works by Comte (*Traité de la propriété* Vols I/II, *Traité de législation* Vols I-IV) and Dunoyer (*Nouveau traité d'économie* Vols I/II).\n\nWhile the corpus discusses free vs. coerced/slave labor productivity (e.g., Dunoyer Vol I ch. 12 critiques coerced labor indirectly via industrial vs. violent regimes; Comte *Traité de la propriété* Vol I ch. 1 critiques slave-based doctrines), no text attributes the specific \"ten English workers... fifty Russian slaves\" or \"English lord... ten times richer... thousands [of slaves]\" comparison to emancipated vs. coerced labor. The corpus (37 works) does not cover every topic; this claim appears absent.",
